1
00:02:11,077 --> 00:02:12,505
Can I help you, sir?

2
00:02:12,673 --> 00:02:15,030
Yes, just help me steady this thing.

3
00:02:18,790 --> 00:02:20,411
Thank you.

4
00:02:21,948 --> 00:02:24,838
Oh, could you give me
a little information?

5
00:02:25,006 --> 00:02:27,228
- Yes, sir.
- Thank you.

6
00:02:32,420 --> 00:02:34,642
Don't wait up for me.

7
00:02:41,828 --> 00:02:45,580
Please call me when we
get to the 18th floor.

8
00:02:58,317 --> 00:03:00,244
Eighteenth floor, sir.

9
00:03:00,909 --> 00:03:02,666
Thank you so much.

10
00:03:02,837 --> 00:03:04,855
If you run into my
stomach on the way down...

11
00:03:05,032 --> 00:03:07,219
...kindly have it sent up.

12
00:03:15,271 --> 00:03:17,696
- Mr. Arden.
- Where's Tony Flagg? I wanna see him.

13
00:03:17,864 --> 00:03:19,450
Well, come in here, please.

14
00:03:19,626 --> 00:03:23,049
Dr. Flagg's busy right now,
but pipe down and I'll take you.

15
00:03:38,142 --> 00:03:39,469
Well, how do you feel now?

16
00:03:39,638 --> 00:03:42,324
I'm not drunk anymore,
Tony. I'm just dizzy.

17
00:03:42,497 --> 00:03:43,789
All right, we'll unwind you.

18
00:03:43,960 --> 00:03:47,009
Say, Steve, when I went to
Switzerland you never drank like this.

19
00:03:47,185 --> 00:03:48,511
How long have you been tight?

20
00:03:48,680 --> 00:03:51,072
Three days: Yesterday,
today and tomorrow.

21
00:03:51,240 --> 00:03:54,164
Because this Amanda What's-Her-Name
broke her engagement to you?

22
00:03:54,331 --> 00:03:57,222
- Yeah, for the third time.
- What happened the other two times?

23
00:03:57,390 --> 00:03:58,375
I got stiff.

24
00:03:58,554 --> 00:04:00,809
I hope she changes her
mind before you get DTs.

25
00:04:00,981 --> 00:04:02,771
That's why I came to
see you, about her.

26
00:04:02,942 --> 00:04:05,628
You came to the right man.
He's straightened out some pips.

27
00:04:05,801 --> 00:04:08,555
We had a dame here yesterday
who was in love with her feet.

28
00:04:08,726 --> 00:04:10,879
Sorry, Steve, I'm no marriage broker.

29
00:04:11,053 --> 00:04:12,708
Now, this Amanda
What's-Her-Name...

30
00:04:12,882 --> 00:04:16,067
Stop calling her What's-Her-Name.
Her name's Cooper, Amanda Cooper.

31
00:04:16,239 --> 00:04:19,526
I don't care what her name is. To
me, she's another maladjusted woman.

32
00:04:19,696 --> 00:04:21,952
She's in perfect order.
She's beautiful, Tony.

33
00:04:22,123 --> 00:04:23,880
That has nothing to do with it either.

34
00:04:24,051 --> 00:04:26,307
Perhaps she's merely
trying to escape reality.

35
00:04:26,478 --> 00:04:28,269
Escape what reality?

36
00:04:28,440 --> 00:04:30,026
- In this case, you.
- What do you...?

37
00:04:30,202 --> 00:04:31,788
We all try to escape reality.

38
00:04:31,963 --> 00:04:34,887
We all wanna be something entirely
different than we really are.

39
00:04:35,056 --> 00:04:38,705
- When I was a kid, I wanted to be a fireman.
- Sure. I wanted to be a cop.

40
00:04:38,878 --> 00:04:41,564
Remember when we were in
college how stage-struck I was?

41
00:04:41,737 --> 00:04:42,960
I wanted to be a dancer.

42
00:04:43,134 --> 00:04:45,060
Psychoanalysis showed me I was wrong.

43
00:04:45,228 --> 00:04:48,843
It's the one way we have of finding out
what we really want and why we want it.

44
00:04:49,018 --> 00:04:51,205
I wanna marry Amanda, and I know why.

45
00:04:51,978 --> 00:04:54,868
Perhaps if I psychoanalyze you,
you won't wanna marry Amanda.

46
00:04:55,036 --> 00:04:57,019
Well, I don't wanna
not wanna marry Amanda.

47
00:04:57,197 --> 00:05:00,517
Easy, Mr. Arden. You don't
have to say everything twice.

48
00:05:00,688 --> 00:05:02,739
- What do you want?
- I wanna marry Amanda.

49
00:05:02,915 --> 00:05:05,340
I guess he wants to marry
What's-Her-Name, all right.

50
00:05:05,508 --> 00:05:07,026
Tony, you've just got to see her.

51
00:05:07,203 --> 00:05:10,025
Why not, doc? She might turn
out to be a very interesting nut.

52
00:05:10,195 --> 00:05:11,917
Maybe this Amanda
What's-Her-Name...

53
00:05:12,090 --> 00:05:13,416
Cooper!

54
00:05:13,586 --> 00:05:16,102
Maybe she prefers staying
on the stage to marrying you.

55
00:05:16,279 --> 00:05:17,831
No, no, no. She wants to marry me.

56
00:05:18,008 --> 00:05:20,093
Why does she keep breaking
off the engagement?

57
00:05:20,268 --> 00:05:23,226
She doesn't know. She says
it's not my fault, it's hers.

58
00:05:23,393 --> 00:05:26,351
At least see her. Maybe you can
figure out what the trouble is.

59
00:05:26,518 --> 00:05:29,103
Well, how do you know she's
willing to be psychoanalyzed?

60
00:05:29,277 --> 00:05:30,761
Oh, she will if I ask her to.

61
00:05:30,939 --> 00:05:34,192
All right. Tell her to come to my
office tomorrow morning at 11:00.

62
00:05:34,363 --> 00:05:35,881
Now, what's her name?

63
00:05:36,059 --> 00:05:37,680
Amanda
What's-Her-Name.

64
00:05:37,854 --> 00:05:39,973
- Cooper.
- Yeah.

65
00:05:46,264 --> 00:05:49,778
Memo to Dr. Jones. Case history
3442, Mrs. Mamie Fletcher.

66
00:05:49,954 --> 00:05:53,071
Dr. Jones, I am turning this case
over to you for further treatment.

67
00:05:53,245 --> 00:05:54,866
My observations are as follows:

68
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:58,395
She's a typical pampered female.
What she needs, instead of a doctor...

69
00:05:58,564 --> 00:06:01,284
...is a good spanking. However...

70
00:06:02,487 --> 00:06:04,142
- Yes, Dr. Powers.
- Dr. Flagg...

71
00:06:04,315 --> 00:06:06,276
...can you come to
my laboratory, please?

72
00:06:06,443 --> 00:06:08,234
There's a Miss Cooper waiting for me.

73
00:06:08,405 --> 00:06:11,295
She's another one of those dizzy,
silly, maladjusted females...

74
00:06:11,463 --> 00:06:14,817
...who can't make up her mind. I'll
probably find out she hasn't got one.

75
00:06:14,987 --> 00:06:17,967
- I just need you for a moment.
- All right, I'll be right out.

76
00:06:26,855 --> 00:06:28,282
How do you do, Miss Cooper?

77
00:06:28,451 --> 00:06:30,502
I am Miss Cooper.

78
00:06:36,695 --> 00:06:38,985
Well, won't you come in, please?

79
00:06:39,155 --> 00:06:41,116
Thank you, doctor.

80
00:06:45,039 --> 00:06:47,963
I've been looking forward with
so much pleasure to this meeting.

81
00:06:48,131 --> 00:06:51,554
I'm sorry, I have to leave you, but
if you'll make yourself comfortable...

82
00:06:51,720 --> 00:06:53,873
...I'll be back, and we
can have a nice visit.

83
00:06:54,048 --> 00:06:57,697
Well, I'm certain I'm going to enjoy
it. Steve thinks so much of you.

84
00:06:57,871 --> 00:07:01,758
Steve's a fine chap. Yes, indeed.

85
00:07:02,227 --> 00:07:03,881
And very lucky too.

86
00:07:04,055 --> 00:07:05,381
Excuse me.

87
00:07:14,692 --> 00:07:18,240
<i>Memo to Dr. Jones. Case history
3442, Mrs. Mamie Fletcher.</i>

88
00:07:18,416 --> 00:07:21,532
<i>Dr. Jones, I am turning this case
over to you for further treatment.</i>

89
00:07:21,707 --> 00:07:24,665
<i>My observations are as follows:
She's a typical pampered female.</i>

90
00:07:24,832 --> 00:07:29,252
<i>What she needs, instead of a doctor,
is a good spanking. However...</i>

91
00:07:30,318 --> 00:07:31,507
<i>Yes, Dr. Powers.</i>

92
00:07:31,680 --> 00:07:33,970
<i>Dr. Flagg, will you come
to my laboratory, please?</i>

93
00:07:34,140 --> 00:07:36,192
<i>There's a Miss Cooper
waiting outside for me.</i>

94
00:07:36,367 --> 00:07:39,257
<i>She's another one of those dizzy,
silly, maladjusted females...</i>

95
00:07:39,426 --> 00:07:42,974
<i>...who can't make up her mind. I'll
probably find out she hasn't got one.</i>

96
00:07:45,377 --> 00:07:47,734
<i>I don't wanna be
disturbed, Miss Adams.</i>

97
00:07:50,530 --> 00:07:52,388
Now there'll be no
more disturbances...

98
00:07:52,557 --> 00:07:55,039
...and we can have that
nice, friendly little chat.

99
00:07:55,216 --> 00:07:57,109
Won't you sit down?

100
00:08:00,702 --> 00:08:02,686
Oh, that's my chair.

101
00:08:02,863 --> 00:08:04,189
Very comfortable.

102
00:08:04,358 --> 00:08:07,215
But I'd planned for you to sit
here. I want you to be relaxed.

103
00:08:07,384 --> 00:08:10,773
I'm perfectly relaxed.
Perhaps you'd better sit there.

104
00:08:14,498 --> 00:08:16,050
Are you always this nervous?

105
00:08:17,124 --> 00:08:20,841
No. Only I usually sit in that chair.

106
00:08:21,014 --> 00:08:24,165
Well, I won't be here very
long, and then you can sit in it.

107
00:08:24,338 --> 00:08:28,260
Oh, now... Now, Miss Cooper,
first let's get to know each other.

108
00:08:28,793 --> 00:08:30,482
Why?

109
00:08:30,721 --> 00:08:32,976
I have to know your mind
as well as I know my own.

110
00:08:33,414 --> 00:08:35,035
Why?

111
00:08:36,040 --> 00:08:39,554
Miss Cooper, you understand the
principle of psychoanalysis, don't you?

112
00:08:40,129 --> 00:08:41,285
No.

113
00:08:41,458 --> 00:08:45,640
Well, you do know that you have two
minds: The conscious and the subconscious.

114
00:08:45,813 --> 00:08:46,867
Really?

115
00:08:47,974 --> 00:08:49,435
The conscious mind is the ego.

116
00:08:49,603 --> 00:08:53,581
That's the thing that says,
"I am I, and you are you. "

117
00:08:54,689 --> 00:08:55,946
Mine never said that.

118
00:09:00,806 --> 00:09:02,427
Let me put it this way, then.

119
00:09:03,665 --> 00:09:07,552
Back here is a jungle full of the
most noble and horrible things.

120
00:09:08,221 --> 00:09:09,547
I don't doubt that.

121
00:09:11,479 --> 00:09:12,940
That's your subconscious mind.

122
00:09:13,108 --> 00:09:15,499
It works all the time,
even when you sleep.

123
00:09:15,667 --> 00:09:18,024
It dreams. It never forgets anything.

124
00:09:18,958 --> 00:09:20,476
Is that so?

125
00:09:22,250 --> 00:09:26,466
Your conscious mind lies here.
It doesn't dream, it thinks.

126
00:09:26,637 --> 00:09:30,083
Now, what we strive for is perfect
coordination between the two.

127
00:09:30,261 --> 00:09:31,882
Do you understand?

128
00:09:32,089 --> 00:09:34,674
No. And I don't believe I care to.

129
00:09:35,048 --> 00:09:37,633
At first I wasn't sure I
wanted to be psychoanalyzed.

130
00:09:37,807 --> 00:09:39,235
And now I'm positive I don't.

131
00:09:39,403 --> 00:09:41,862
Now, you mustn't put a wall
between us, Miss Cooper.

132
00:09:42,029 --> 00:09:44,783
To psychoanalyze you, I
must interpret your dreams.

133
00:09:44,955 --> 00:09:47,176
What sort of things do you dream?

134
00:09:47,349 --> 00:09:48,776
I don't dream.

135
00:09:48,944 --> 00:09:51,925
- Oh, come, now. Everybody dreams.
- I don't.

136
00:09:52,102 --> 00:09:55,684
I wish you'd please understand that I'm
only trying to help you find yourself.

137
00:09:55,858 --> 00:09:58,782
Well, if I ever get
lost, I'll call on you.

138
00:10:02,241 --> 00:10:06,458
Attention, everybody. Having tied on the
shoot-off, Judge Travers and Mr. Arden...

139
00:10:06,629 --> 00:10:11,639
...have decided to break the tie by
a miss-and-out event at single bird.

140
00:10:13,212 --> 00:10:14,673
Pull.

141
00:10:18,164 --> 00:10:19,491
- Lost bird.
- Too bad, Stephen.

142
00:10:19,661 --> 00:10:22,245
You've been shooting as
if you'd been on a bender.

143
00:10:22,420 --> 00:10:24,278
I feel as if I had been.

144
00:10:24,448 --> 00:10:26,069
Nice shooting.

145
00:10:26,975 --> 00:10:29,434
Tony, what did you do to Amanda?

146
00:10:29,601 --> 00:10:30,825
What did I do?

147
00:10:30,997 --> 00:10:33,921
Oh, I'm sorry. I want you to meet
Amanda's Aunt Cora. Dr. Flagg.

148
00:10:34,088 --> 00:10:36,072
- How do you do?
- Amanda's furious with you.

149
00:10:36,249 --> 00:10:38,142
What happened? She wouldn't tell me.

150
00:10:38,311 --> 00:10:39,603
She's a very curious case.

151
00:10:39,773 --> 00:10:41,598
At first, she was
sweet and charming...

152
00:10:41,768 --> 00:10:44,319
...then, for no reason at
all, she became argumentative.

153
00:10:44,494 --> 00:10:46,545
You should hear what
she thinks about you.

154
00:10:47,253 --> 00:10:49,768
- What?
- She thinks you're a quack.

155
00:10:49,946 --> 00:10:51,532
Oh, she does?

156
00:10:53,005 --> 00:10:54,228
Pull.

157
00:10:59,520 --> 00:11:03,374
Very good. Very good, Your Honor.
Your shooting was superb, Your Honor.

158
00:11:03,543 --> 00:11:04,971
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

159
00:11:05,139 --> 00:11:07,065
His Honor Judge Travers, Dr. Flagg.

160
00:11:07,233 --> 00:11:09,318
- Judge Travers.
- How do you do?

161
00:11:09,493 --> 00:11:12,610
Well, I beat you today, Stephen.
That makes us even-steven.

162
00:11:12,785 --> 00:11:14,904
Well, just wait for the finals.

163
00:11:15,079 --> 00:11:18,467
- How'd you like my exhibition, Cora?
- Pretty good, Joe, I guess.

164
00:11:18,636 --> 00:11:20,529
Pretty good? It was pretty perfect.

165
00:11:20,697 --> 00:11:23,179
If you could only play
bridge the way you play scat.

166
00:11:23,356 --> 00:11:26,144
It's skeet, and besides,
you don't play it.

167
00:11:26,714 --> 00:11:30,658
That's what I mean, Joe.
You don't play bridge either.

168
00:11:43,834 --> 00:11:46,622
You're getting terrific lengths
with your drives, Dr. Flagg.

169
00:11:47,624 --> 00:11:50,877
Thank you, Mr. MacPherson.
You're very, very encouraging.

170
00:11:51,048 --> 00:11:53,100
It's about time, Mac.

171
00:12:18,075 --> 00:12:21,090
Quack. Have you any suggestions?

172
00:12:21,266 --> 00:12:23,725
Maybe you were hitting it
with your subconscious mind.

173
00:12:23,893 --> 00:12:25,910
You know, the one that dreams.

174
00:12:26,087 --> 00:12:27,775
Smack it once with your conscious.

175
00:12:27,949 --> 00:12:29,501
It'll go when I hit it.

176
00:12:29,677 --> 00:12:32,601
What happened to that theory of
coordination you were hot about?

177
00:12:32,769 --> 00:12:36,351
- Doing several things at the same time.
- Oh, that.

178
00:12:36,691 --> 00:12:39,649
Murph, set them up.

179
00:15:36,076 --> 00:15:38,467
What's the matter, Aunt
Cora? Did you lose something?

180
00:15:38,637 --> 00:15:40,688
Not that I know of. Why?

181
00:15:40,863 --> 00:15:42,915
You keep looking back all the time.

182
00:15:43,091 --> 00:15:45,347
Oh, I was looking for that Dr. Quack.

183
00:15:45,518 --> 00:15:47,003
Flagg?

184
00:15:48,344 --> 00:15:49,771
Is he coming, Steve?

185
00:15:49,939 --> 00:15:51,956
It seems silly to keep it a secret.

186
00:15:52,134 --> 00:15:54,718
He said he wanted to
psychoanalyze you on your bicycle.

187
00:15:54,892 --> 00:15:56,910
Oh, so that's why we came.

188
00:15:57,086 --> 00:16:00,532
I wouldn't mind being
analyzed by him on my bicycle.

189
00:16:00,710 --> 00:16:02,432
Or on anything, come to think of it.

190
00:16:08,024 --> 00:16:10,041
Well, well, what luck.

191
00:16:10,218 --> 00:16:13,334
- None.
- Well, Tony, what a pleasant surprise.

192
00:16:16,135 --> 00:16:19,354
Steve, can't you see that Dr.
Flagg wants to ride with me alone?

193
00:16:19,526 --> 00:16:20,920
Oh, sorry, Tony.

194
00:16:21,088 --> 00:16:22,981
Want to drop back here
with me, Aunt Cora?

195
00:16:23,150 --> 00:16:25,303
All right, if you
don't try to amuse me.

196
00:16:29,100 --> 00:16:30,460
Well?

197
00:16:30,629 --> 00:16:32,215
Will you please tell me something?

198
00:16:32,391 --> 00:16:35,350
Why were you suddenly
so unfriendly yesterday?

199
00:16:35,516 --> 00:16:38,837
Quote, "Just another one of those
dizzy, silly, maladjusted females...

200
00:16:39,007 --> 00:16:41,330
...who can't make up
her mind," unquote.

201
00:16:42,863 --> 00:16:47,011
Well, of course, that
was before I met you.

202
00:16:47,550 --> 00:16:50,009
Well, I can forgive you
for saying I have no mind...

203
00:16:50,177 --> 00:16:53,860
...but I'm afraid maybe you're
right about my being maladjusted.

204
00:16:54,032 --> 00:16:56,617
We're never really afraid
of anything we understand.

205
00:16:56,792 --> 00:16:58,344
That sounds as if it makes sense.

206
00:16:58,521 --> 00:17:02,204
Of course, if we know the reason
for most fears, we can dispel them.

207
00:17:02,376 --> 00:17:05,130
Very often, fear is
just a simple phobia:

208
00:17:05,303 --> 00:17:08,748
Afraid of darkness,
afraid of great heights...

209
00:17:08,926 --> 00:17:12,315
...afraid of marriage.

210
00:17:21,093 --> 00:17:24,051
- You better put on your brakes, doctor.
- What?

211
00:17:24,217 --> 00:17:25,736
It's getting steep.

212
00:17:32,329 --> 00:17:34,154
Hey, look out.

213
00:17:34,424 --> 00:17:35,942
Take it easy, doctor.

214
00:17:36,451 --> 00:17:37,845
I can't.

215
00:17:38,013 --> 00:17:39,532
Now, don't show off.

216
00:17:39,709 --> 00:17:41,364
I'm not, my chairs broken.

217
00:17:43,599 --> 00:17:45,820
Please, Miss Cooper, look out.

218
00:17:56,797 --> 00:17:58,757
Doctor, are you all right?

219
00:17:58,924 --> 00:18:00,613
Yes, I guess so.

220
00:18:04,376 --> 00:18:06,031
You win.

221
00:18:25,386 --> 00:18:27,142
- Shall you order now, Mr. Arden?
- No.

222
00:18:27,314 --> 00:18:30,396
- We'll wait for Miss Cooper and Dr. Flagg.
- Very good, sir.

223
00:18:31,270 --> 00:18:33,627
Is this one of your
silent treatments, doctor?

224
00:18:33,797 --> 00:18:37,050
Trying to think of some mental
prescription that might induce dreams.

225
00:18:37,220 --> 00:18:39,113
Here we go again.

226
00:18:39,415 --> 00:18:42,634
I hate to be persistent, but
I'm trying to help you and Steve.

227
00:18:42,805 --> 00:18:44,823
And I have to dream?

228
00:18:44,999 --> 00:18:49,918
Well, it would simplify matters,
and it's possible to make you dream.

229
00:18:50,085 --> 00:18:53,338
Well, I'll try anything, if
you can guarantee the dream.

230
00:18:53,510 --> 00:18:54,733
Good.

231
00:18:54,939 --> 00:19:00,482
I imagine women find Dr. Flagg
very charming, especially girls.

232
00:19:00,657 --> 00:19:04,579
Why, Tony's a doctor.
Amanda's only his patient.

233
00:19:04,979 --> 00:19:07,869
He's all wrapped up
in his work, isn't he?

234
00:19:09,300 --> 00:19:10,989
Then you'll eat whatever I order?

235
00:19:11,462 --> 00:19:14,443
To paraphrase, doctor,
you're the doctor.

236
00:19:21,568 --> 00:19:22,860
Behold the guinea pig.

237
00:19:23,030 --> 00:19:25,489
Aunt Cora, Steve, I'm
on a diet to dream.

238
00:19:25,657 --> 00:19:28,309
How marvelous. Who's the lucky man?

239
00:19:28,482 --> 00:19:31,905
Miss Cooper is going to dream tonight
by eating dream-provoking foods.

240
00:19:32,073 --> 00:19:33,829
Tomorrow I'll explain
her dream to her.

241
00:19:34,001 --> 00:19:36,982
I'd eat anything if I thought it
would make my dreams come true.

242
00:19:38,422 --> 00:19:41,245
May I recommend the filet
mignon smothered with mushrooms.

243
00:19:41,414 --> 00:19:44,134
No, thank you. Miss Cooper
would prefer a seafood cocktail.

244
00:19:44,307 --> 00:19:46,596
- Seafood cocktail.
- With whipped cream.

245
00:19:47,465 --> 00:19:49,358
Seafood cocktail with whipped cream?

246
00:19:49,526 --> 00:19:52,178
But not too much whipped
cream, just a soupçon.

247
00:19:52,352 --> 00:19:55,310
- Soupçon.
- Next, I'd like a largish Welsh rarebit.

248
00:19:55,476 --> 00:19:58,299
Instead of the seafood
cocktail with whipped cream?

249
00:19:58,468 --> 00:19:59,692
No.

250
00:19:59,865 --> 00:20:02,947
You mean, madame, she
wishes to eat them both?

251
00:20:03,123 --> 00:20:06,047
- Yes.
- Double up on the cheese.

252
00:20:06,912 --> 00:20:09,836
- I know something that tastes perfectly vile.
- Good, what is it?

253
00:20:10,003 --> 00:20:11,589
Lobster with gobs of mayonnaise.

254
00:20:11,766 --> 00:20:13,318
- Wonderful.
- Oh, yes.

255
00:20:13,494 --> 00:20:14,979
Instead of the Welsh rarebit...

256
00:20:15,156 --> 00:20:17,208
...and seafood cocktail
with whipped cream?

257
00:20:17,384 --> 00:20:19,606
- No, all of them.
- That lobster sounds wonderful.

258
00:20:19,777 --> 00:20:20,967
Bring me an order of that.

259
00:20:21,140 --> 00:20:24,325
Pardon, madame, but that all
makes a very bad combination.

260
00:20:24,498 --> 00:20:25,721
Yes, I know.

261
00:20:25,894 --> 00:20:28,014
Now all you need is
a good, solid dessert.

262
00:20:31,280 --> 00:20:35,099
May I suggest cucumbers
and buttermilk.

263
00:20:35,269 --> 00:20:36,753
- Yes.
- Wonderful.

264
00:20:36,964 --> 00:20:39,617
And a side order of
strawberry shortcake.

265
00:20:39,790 --> 00:20:42,544
- Have you got all that?
- Yes.

266
00:20:44,012 --> 00:20:45,939
<i>Seafood cocktail with whipped cream.</i>

267
00:20:46,405 --> 00:20:48,389
<i>A largish Welsh rarebit.</i>

268
00:20:48,965 --> 00:20:51,651
<i>Lobster with gobs of mayonnaise.</i>

269
00:20:52,422 --> 00:20:55,437
<i>Cucumbers and buttermilk.</i>

270
00:21:06,185 --> 00:21:09,200
I think I better go home
and go to bed, Amanda.

271
00:21:09,376 --> 00:21:11,234
Oh, no, the furs just beginning.

272
00:21:11,405 --> 00:21:14,329
Mine got near the end when you
ate that second Welsh rarebit.

273
00:21:14,496 --> 00:21:17,975
- Please, let's forget the experiment.
- Don't you feel sleepy, Miss Cooper?

274
00:21:18,153 --> 00:21:19,513
Never felt better in my life.

275
00:21:19,682 --> 00:21:22,539
In fact, now I'm sorry I had
to pass up that second lobster.

276
00:21:22,707 --> 00:21:24,463
<i>Oh, Amanda, please.</i>

277
00:21:24,636 --> 00:21:26,222
Are you sure you're not sleepy?

278
00:21:26,397 --> 00:21:28,822
Not a bit. I'll go
mix you some drinks.

279
00:21:36,504 --> 00:21:38,521
Well, as long as your
niece feels so well...

280
00:21:38,698 --> 00:21:42,619
...and Steve is obviously not so
good, I think I'd better see him home.

281
00:21:42,787 --> 00:21:44,180
Good night, Miss Cooper.

282
00:21:45,113 --> 00:21:46,575
Good night.

283
00:21:49,169 --> 00:21:51,288
Come on, there's nothing
really wrong with you.

284
00:21:51,463 --> 00:21:54,649
It's all in your mind. Think you're
all right and you'll be all right.

285
00:21:54,821 --> 00:21:56,838
Oh, but those cucumbers
and buttermilk...

286
00:21:57,015 --> 00:22:00,131
...and lobsters and
strawberry shortca...

287
00:22:02,533 --> 00:22:04,426
See what I mean?

288
00:22:04,594 --> 00:22:07,779
Oh, doctor, here's the sedative
you asked me to bring over.

289
00:22:10,844 --> 00:22:13,892
Connors, you better go in there,
give Miss Cooper a teaspoonful.

290
00:22:14,069 --> 00:22:17,492
- It's very important. Make her take it.
- Miss Cooper, yes, sir.

291
00:22:19,819 --> 00:22:23,005
Steve, maybe we better walk down.

292
00:22:26,668 --> 00:22:28,787
- Are you Miss Cooper?
- Yes.

293
00:22:28,961 --> 00:22:31,681
Dr. Flagg sent me to take care of you.

294
00:22:31,854 --> 00:22:34,936
Well, how nice of Dr. Flagg.

295
00:22:35,112 --> 00:22:36,698
Come in.

296
00:22:40,431 --> 00:22:43,015
What does he think should be done?

297
00:22:43,190 --> 00:22:47,168
Well, I'm gonna give you something
that'll relax you completely.

298
00:22:49,273 --> 00:22:50,894
Sit down.

299
00:22:51,501 --> 00:22:54,324
Perhaps we'd better
talk this over first.

300
00:22:54,493 --> 00:22:57,111
Now, first, I want you
to have confidence in me.

301
00:22:57,286 --> 00:23:00,300
I have a feeling I'm going to
have complete confidence in you.

302
00:23:00,477 --> 00:23:01,803
Well, that's just fine.

303
00:23:04,598 --> 00:23:06,582
I'm so glad you're a
friend of Dr. Flagg's.

304
00:23:06,759 --> 00:23:08,946
I have no confidence in strangers.

305
00:23:09,485 --> 00:23:11,604
Dr. Flagg is a remarkable man.

306
00:23:11,779 --> 00:23:15,565
Dr. Flagg always knows what's best.

307
00:23:15,735 --> 00:23:17,321
I can believe that.

308
00:23:17,497 --> 00:23:18,924
Now...

309
00:23:19,256 --> 00:23:21,545
I want you to take just
a little sip of this.

310
00:23:21,716 --> 00:23:24,141
All right. What is it?

311
00:23:24,309 --> 00:23:28,390
It... It'll help relax you.

312
00:23:30,625 --> 00:23:33,878
All right, but I'm not at all nervous.

313
00:23:37,174 --> 00:23:39,101
Now, go right in and go to bed.

314
00:24:20,790 --> 00:24:22,251
<i>Cocktail with whipped cream.</i>

315
00:24:22,419 --> 00:24:23,903
<i>A good, solid dessert.</i>

316
00:24:24,081 --> 00:24:26,539
<i>Cucumbers and buttermilk.</i>

317
00:24:26,707 --> 00:24:29,688
<i>Gobs of mayonnaise.
Strawberry shortcake.</i>

318
00:24:45,656 --> 00:24:51,368
<i>Strange how a dreary
world Can suddenly change</i>

319
00:24:51,540 --> 00:24:55,858
<i>To a world as bright
As the evening star</i>

320
00:24:57,790 --> 00:25:03,673
<i>Queer what a difference
When your vision is clear</i>

321
00:25:03,906 --> 00:25:09,086
<i>And you see things as they really are</i>

322
00:25:11,120 --> 00:25:15,564
<i>I used to be colorblind But I met you</i>

323
00:25:15,741 --> 00:25:18,960
<i>And now I find There's
green in the grass</i>

324
00:25:19,132 --> 00:25:20,854
<i>There's gold in the moon</i>

325
00:25:21,027 --> 00:25:23,577
<i>There's blue in the sky</i>

326
00:25:23,752 --> 00:25:29,828
<i>That semicircle That
was always hanging about</i>

327
00:25:30,534 --> 00:25:35,181
<i>Is not a storm cloud It's a rainbow</i>

328
00:25:35,354 --> 00:25:39,208
<i>You brought the colors out</i>

329
00:25:39,378 --> 00:25:43,889
<i>Believe me, it's really
true Till I met you</i>

330
00:25:44,064 --> 00:25:47,543
<i>I never knew a setting sun</i>

331
00:25:47,722 --> 00:25:51,575
<i>Could paint such beautiful skies</i>

332
00:25:51,744 --> 00:25:57,026
<i>I never knew There
were such lovely colors</i>

333
00:25:57,196 --> 00:26:02,613
<i>And the big surprise Is
the red in your cheeks</i>

334
00:26:02,781 --> 00:26:04,605
<i>The gold in your hair</i>

335
00:26:04,775 --> 00:26:07,563
<i>The blue in your eyes</i>

336
00:28:18,646 --> 00:28:20,630
Aunt Cora, do you believe in dreams?

337
00:28:20,807 --> 00:28:25,386
Certainly. I had a humdinger
last night. If it was a dream.

338
00:28:25,562 --> 00:28:29,744
I had the loveliest time in
mine. Everything happened.

339
00:28:29,917 --> 00:28:33,033
I wasrt so lucky. Nothing happened.

340
00:28:33,706 --> 00:28:35,927
- Lobster?
- Breakfast, lunch or dinner.

341
00:28:36,100 --> 00:28:37,958
I'm taking no chances.

342
00:28:38,127 --> 00:28:40,314
I wanna pick up where
I left off in my dream...

343
00:28:40,687 --> 00:28:41,775
...if I can.

344
00:28:43,613 --> 00:28:46,004
- A big gob of mayonnaise.
- Mayonnaise?

345
00:28:46,172 --> 00:28:48,031
Yes, for the lobster.

346
00:28:50,627 --> 00:28:53,052
In my dream, I was with
the most wonderful man.

347
00:28:53,220 --> 00:28:55,339
Me too. It was so realistic.

348
00:28:55,514 --> 00:28:58,596
- He was all in white.
- Are you sure it was a dream?

349
00:28:58,772 --> 00:29:01,559
Positive. Nothing like that
ever happened to me in real life.

350
00:29:01,730 --> 00:29:04,778
Wonder if it's possible to fall
in love with a man you dream about.

351
00:29:04,955 --> 00:29:06,507
Oh, I'm positive.

352
00:29:07,747 --> 00:29:09,436
Come in.

353
00:29:09,809 --> 00:29:11,531
- Good morning.
- Good morning, Stephen.

354
00:29:11,703 --> 00:29:14,185
Good morning, Amanda. How do you feel?

355
00:29:14,363 --> 00:29:15,791
- Marvelous.
- Did you sleep well?

356
00:29:15,958 --> 00:29:17,250
- Marvelous.
- Well, good.

357
00:29:17,422 --> 00:29:19,507
I thought I'd drive you
over to see Dr. Flagg.

358
00:29:19,681 --> 00:29:20,905
- Marvelous.
- Amanda...

359
00:29:21,078 --> 00:29:23,300
...do you realize
you're being repetitious?

360
00:29:23,471 --> 00:29:26,950
I hate to mention that awful food you
both ate, but I was worried about you.

361
00:29:27,129 --> 00:29:29,520
Just thinking about it
kept me awake all night.

362
00:29:29,821 --> 00:29:31,282
Mayonnaise.

363
00:29:31,450 --> 00:29:33,105
Marvelous.

364
00:29:42,221 --> 00:29:43,977
Tony, it happened. Congratulate us.

365
00:29:44,149 --> 00:29:46,902
- Did you get married?
- Not quite, but Amanda dreamed.

366
00:29:47,075 --> 00:29:49,557
Well, Miss Cooper. So our
little experiment worked.

367
00:29:49,734 --> 00:29:51,026
Yes, doctor, marvelously.

368
00:29:51,197 --> 00:29:53,916
Sit right down now, Amanda,
and tell us all about it.

369
00:29:54,089 --> 00:29:56,604
Steve, this is a matter
between Miss Cooper and myself.

370
00:29:56,782 --> 00:30:00,760
Why? We're all in on it. If there's anything
I shouldn't know, I ought to know it now.

371
00:30:00,937 --> 00:30:03,862
Women tell their doctors things
they don't want anyone to hear.

372
00:30:04,029 --> 00:30:07,746
- I know, but I'm gonna be her husband.
- Especially husbands.

373
00:30:11,441 --> 00:30:14,694
Now, Miss Cooper, tell
me all about your dream.

374
00:30:16,860 --> 00:30:19,977
- Did you dream of anyone in particular?
- Yes.

375
00:30:20,151 --> 00:30:21,545
Fine. Who was it?

376
00:30:25,471 --> 00:30:26,830
Oh, I can't.

377
00:30:27,099 --> 00:30:29,185
Now, Miss Cooper, don't
think of me as anyone.

378
00:30:29,360 --> 00:30:32,545
Just think of me as your doctor.
You must have every confidence in me.

379
00:30:32,718 --> 00:30:34,145
Oh, I have.

380
00:30:34,314 --> 00:30:35,775
Then tell me all about it.

381
00:30:40,696 --> 00:30:42,124
I can't.

382
00:30:42,292 --> 00:30:44,049
Very well.

383
00:30:44,918 --> 00:30:47,899
Thank you very much. That's all.

384
00:30:48,242 --> 00:30:50,260
Well, doctor, when do
you wanna see me again?

385
00:30:50,436 --> 00:30:52,159
There's no point in seeing you again.

386
00:30:52,331 --> 00:30:54,382
Oh, but you must. I mean...

387
00:30:54,559 --> 00:30:56,848
Well, I'll recommend
several other doctors to you.

388
00:30:57,019 --> 00:31:00,101
And no doubt you'll find one in
whom you'll have more confidence.

389
00:31:00,277 --> 00:31:01,863
But I don't want another doctor.

390
00:31:02,038 --> 00:31:05,087
Miss Cooper, I was persuaded
by Steve to talk to you.

391
00:31:05,263 --> 00:31:09,049
And from what I see, there's
nothing very wrong with you.

392
00:31:10,483 --> 00:31:11,706
Are you sure?

393
00:31:11,879 --> 00:31:14,860
Compared to complex cases,
which really need me...

394
00:31:15,037 --> 00:31:16,465
...no.

395
00:31:16,632 --> 00:31:19,919
Oh, what... Oh, well, then...

396
00:31:20,090 --> 00:31:22,913
...I guess I'd better
tell you my dream.

397
00:31:24,910 --> 00:31:27,733
I've had it for 11 straight years.

398
00:31:29,166 --> 00:31:30,956
Tell me about it.

399
00:31:44,524 --> 00:31:48,672
Well, you've heard of Little
Red Riding Hood and the wolf?

400
00:31:48,846 --> 00:31:50,069
Yes, I have.

401
00:31:50,241 --> 00:31:52,293
Well, that's what I dreamed about.

402
00:31:52,469 --> 00:31:54,725
You dreamed you were
Little Red Riding Hood?

403
00:31:54,895 --> 00:31:57,252
No, I was the wolf.

404
00:31:58,021 --> 00:31:59,244
What did you do?

405
00:32:00,680 --> 00:32:02,573
I snarled.

406
00:32:06,332 --> 00:32:08,451
And then I...

407
00:32:08,924 --> 00:32:13,900
All of a sudden, I became
Little Red Riding Hood...

408
00:32:14,144 --> 00:32:18,065
...and then suddenly
I was a lot of numbers.

409
00:32:18,233 --> 00:32:22,154
- Numbers?
- Yes, I... I was a radio dial.

410
00:32:22,322 --> 00:32:25,676
Understandable. That's part of your
profession, singing on the radio?

411
00:32:25,846 --> 00:32:28,736
Yes. Yes, but you
haven't heard it all yet.

412
00:32:28,904 --> 00:32:31,862
It seemed that all night long,
there were thousands of people...

413
00:32:32,029 --> 00:32:35,043
...that kept turning me
off and turning me on...

414
00:32:35,220 --> 00:32:36,942
...turning me off and turning me on.

415
00:32:37,115 --> 00:32:41,728
Half the time I was singing, and
the other half I was advertising.

416
00:32:41,902 --> 00:32:47,910
Then... Then there were voices.
Voices, thousands of voices...

417
00:32:48,085 --> 00:32:51,905
...and then they started to
chase me, to persecute me.

418
00:32:52,074 --> 00:32:54,760
- Who?
- My persecutors.

419
00:32:54,934 --> 00:32:57,620
- Persecution complex.
- Yes.

420
00:32:57,859 --> 00:33:02,109
And then... Then I was
running away from them...

421
00:33:02,281 --> 00:33:04,434
...and I was gaining
miles ahead of them...

422
00:33:04,607 --> 00:33:08,789
...when all of a sudden,
I turned into a maple tree.

423
00:33:08,962 --> 00:33:13,439
And then I took a
shortcut across the stream.

424
00:33:13,617 --> 00:33:18,298
And a huge fish raised itself out
of the water and snapped at me.

425
00:33:18,470 --> 00:33:19,693
It was a dogfish.

426
00:33:19,866 --> 00:33:23,686
Then I looked behind me, and
thousands... Thousands of squirrels...

427
00:33:23,856 --> 00:33:27,743
...had jumped the river and like a pack
of hungry wolves were rushing at me.

428
00:33:27,911 --> 00:33:30,268
- Oh, I was frantic.
- Yes.

429
00:33:30,437 --> 00:33:31,956
- They were coming closer.
- Yes.

430
00:33:32,133 --> 00:33:33,889
- They were on me from every side.
- Yes.

431
00:33:34,061 --> 00:33:35,750
- From the front.
- Yes.

432
00:33:35,923 --> 00:33:37,407
- From the back.
- Yes.

433
00:33:37,585 --> 00:33:40,872
From all sides of me,
their teeth snapping at me.

434
00:33:41,042 --> 00:33:43,264
- I couldn't escape.
- What happened?

435
00:33:44,233 --> 00:33:45,785
They got me.

436
00:33:47,824 --> 00:33:51,269
- Please, could I have just a little water?
- Oh, yes, of course.

437
00:33:57,630 --> 00:33:58,854
Yes, Dr. Flagg?

438
00:33:59,027 --> 00:34:01,612
Dr. Powers, will you please
come right over to my office.

439
00:34:06,241 --> 00:34:08,564
Oh, thank you, doctor.

440
00:34:11,692 --> 00:34:14,617
- Are you all right?
- Yes, quite all right. Thank you, doctor.

441
00:34:14,784 --> 00:34:17,742
Then if you'll excuse
me, I'll just be a moment.

442
00:34:23,494 --> 00:34:26,044
- She's wonderful, Steve.
- Of course she is. I know that.

443
00:34:26,221 --> 00:34:30,267
She's a mass of the most horrible neuroses
and inhibitions I've come in contact with.

444
00:34:30,442 --> 00:34:32,664
- What's the matter with her?
- What is it, doctor?

445
00:34:32,835 --> 00:34:35,850
I've run across the most beautiful
case of complex maladjustments.

446
00:34:36,027 --> 00:34:37,716
- Where?
- In there, in my office.

447
00:34:37,888 --> 00:34:39,872
This is one of the
happiest days of my life.

448
00:34:40,049 --> 00:34:42,305
- What did you find, old chap?
- Vulpine complex.

449
00:34:42,476 --> 00:34:44,494
- Child psychosis, a classic example.
- No.

450
00:34:44,670 --> 00:34:47,186
- Yes.
- My congratulations, old chap. I envy you.

451
00:34:47,363 --> 00:34:49,619
- What's wrong with her?
- I'll find a million more.

452
00:34:50,489 --> 00:34:52,880
She's untapped. She's got
everything wrong with her.

453
00:34:53,050 --> 00:34:54,738
- You mean Amanda?
- Follow it through.

454
00:34:54,911 --> 00:34:57,960
- How long do you think it'll take?
- Years. Five, 10. We never know.

455
00:34:58,136 --> 00:34:59,791
Will you assist me in my laboratory?

456
00:34:59,964 --> 00:35:02,287
Delighted. I can hardly wait.

457
00:35:02,690 --> 00:35:05,013
Mind telling me what's the
matter with Miss Cooper?

458
00:35:05,184 --> 00:35:08,732
Not at all. She sounds
like a textbook case.

459
00:35:11,034 --> 00:35:12,689
Well, how do we feel now?

460
00:35:12,862 --> 00:35:14,948
A little tired, doctor.

461
00:35:15,223 --> 00:35:16,480
But, oh, so relieved.

462
00:35:16,652 --> 00:35:18,976
Now, there's absolutely
nothing to be afraid of.

463
00:35:19,146 --> 00:35:21,503
I know that, doctor,
because I'm in your hands.

464
00:35:21,672 --> 00:35:25,650
Good. Now, first, I'm gonna
give you an anesthetic.

465
00:35:25,827 --> 00:35:27,051
Well, what for?

466
00:35:27,224 --> 00:35:29,615
It'll effect a temporary
release of any inhibitions.

467
00:35:29,784 --> 00:35:32,708
It's not a cure, but I can get
an idea of what's wrong with you.

468
00:35:32,875 --> 00:35:35,493
But is an anesthetic necessary?

469
00:35:35,668 --> 00:35:36,891
It's the simplest way.

470
00:35:37,064 --> 00:35:39,024
The effect will wear
off in an hour or so.

471
00:35:39,192 --> 00:35:40,710
And meanwhile I can talk to you.

472
00:35:40,886 --> 00:35:43,278
If you want to talk to
